Q-2.6 Draw the histogram of measured observations; specify title, color, x axis label, y axis label, x axis range, y axis range and the number of intervals.
Calculate the mean and median of the data, and add them as lines on to the plot.

hist(pig$y, 
     main = "current amplitude",
     breaks = 20)
abline(v = mean(pig$y))

# Histogram using ggplot
ggplot(pig, aes(x = y))+
  geom_histogram(color = 'black', alpha = 0.5, bins = 40)+
  labs( title = "Current Amplitude",
        x = "Peak Count",
        y = "Frequency")+
  theme_bw(base_size = 10)+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 18, face = "bold"),
        axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"))+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = mean(y)), colour = 'red', linetype = 'dashed', size = 1)+
  geom_vline(aes(xintercept = median(y)), colour = 'blue', linetype = 'dashed', size = 1)+
  
  annotate("text", x = mean(pig$y), y = Inf, label = paste("Mean:", round(mean(pig$y), 2)),
           vjust = 1.5, hjust = -0.1, color = "red", size = 4, fontface = "bold") +
  annotate("text", x = median(pig$y), y = Inf, label = paste("Median:", round(median(pig$y), 2)),
           vjust = 3, hjust = -0.1, color = "blue", size = 4, fontface = "bold")

cats$Sex <- factor(cats$Sex, levels = c("F", "M"))

# Body Weight boxplot using ggplot
ggplot(cats, aes(x = Sex, y = Bwt, fill = Sex))+
  geom_boxplot(color = 'black', alpha = 0.9, outlier.color = 'blue')+
  stat_boxplot(geom = 'errorbar', width = 0.2)+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(F = 'skyblue',M = 'lightgreen'))+
  theme_bw()

# Heart Weight boxplot using ggplot
ggplot(cats, aes(x = Sex, y = Hwt, fill = Sex))+
  geom_boxplot(color = 'black', alpha = 0.5, outlier.color = "red", outlier.alpha = 1)+
  stat_boxplot(geom = 'errorbar', width = 0.2)+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(F = 'skyblue', M = 'lightgreen'))+
  theme_bw()

Example - 05

Draw the scatterplot of body weight (on x axis) vs heart weight (on y axis).
Specify title, color, x axis label, y axis label, x axis range, y axis range, choose a type of point

plot(x = cats$Bwt, y = cats$Hwt, pch = 19, col = "darkred")

# Scatterplot using ggplot
ggplot(cats, aes(x = Bwt, y = Hwt))+
  geom_point(color = 'darkred', alpha = 0.9, size = 2)+
  theme_bw()+
  labs(title = "scatterplot of body weight vs heart weight",
       x = "Body Weight",
       y = "Heart Weight")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 18, face = 'bold'),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 14,face = 'bold'))+
  geom_smooth(method = lm,se = F, linetype = 'solid', color = 'green')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

Exercise - 02

‘spideramputation’ data contains speeds of male spiders, before and after their one arm is amputated. In a sipder species, male spiders has been observed to voruntarily amputate one of their organs just before sexual maturity. The relevant question is that does males do this to increase their speed performance (because their weight will decrease) to find a female partner. To test the hypothesis, researchers recorded the speed of male spiders before and after one of their legs amputated.
- Draw an appropriate plot for the data and specify the following arguments: x axis label, y axis label, title, color, labels
 - By just looking at the graph, which group seems to have higher speed?
 - Calculate the mean and sd for both groups. We have to do a statistical analysis before jumping to any conclusion but by observing the plot and the the mean and sd values, what can you comment on the hypothesis?

spider <- read.csv("data/spider.csv", row.names = 1)
head(spider)
##   spider speed treatment
## 1      1  1.25    before
## 2      2  2.94    before
## 3      3  2.38    before
## 4      4  3.09    before
## 5      5  3.41    before
## 6      6  3.00    before
summary(spider)
##      spider          speed        treatment        
##  Min.   : 1.00   Min.   :1.250   Length:32         
##  1st Qu.: 4.75   1st Qu.:2.730   Class :character  
##  Median : 8.50   Median :3.195   Mode  :character  
##  Mean   : 8.50   Mean   :3.261                     
##  3rd Qu.:12.25   3rd Qu.:3.527                     
##  Max.   :16.00   Max.   :5.450
spider$treatment <- factor(spider$treatment, levels = c("before", "after"))
ggplot(spider, aes(x = treatment, y = speed, fill = treatment))+
  geom_boxplot(color = 'black', alpha = 0.5, outlier.colour = 'blue')+
  stat_boxplot(geom = "errorbar", width = 0.2)+
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(before = 'skyblue', after = 'lightgreen'))+
  labs(title = "Amputation effect on speed",
       x = "Treatment",
       y = "Speed")+
  theme_bw(base_size = 10)+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 18, face = "bold"),
        axis.title = element_text(face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(face = "bold"))

Exercise - 04

data("DNase")
head(DNase)
## Grouped Data: density ~ conc | Run
##   Run       conc density
## 1   1 0.04882812   0.017
## 2   1 0.04882812   0.018
## 3   1 0.19531250   0.121
## 4   1 0.19531250   0.124
## 5   1 0.39062500   0.206
## 6   1 0.39062500   0.215
dnase.r3 <- subset(DNase, Run == 3, select = c(conc, density))
dnase.r5 <- subset(DNase, Run == 5, select = c(conc, density))
dnase.r8 <- subset(DNase, Run == 8, select = c(conc, density))
dnase.r11 <- subset(DNase, Run == 11, select = c(conc, density))

Combining in data.frame object

dnase.combined <- rbind(
  data.frame(conc = dnase.r3$conc, density = dnase.r3$density, replicate = "ELISA Assay Run 3"),
  data.frame(conc = dnase.r5$conc, density = dnase.r5$density, replicate = "ELISA Assay Run 5"),
  data.frame(conc = dnase.r8$conc, density = dnase.r8$density, replicate = "ELISA Assay Run 8"),
  data.frame(conc = dnase.r11$conc, density = dnase.r11$density, replicate = "ELISA Assay Run 11")
)

Plotting the scatterplot

ggplot(dnase.combined, aes(x = conc, y = density))+
  geom_point()+
  facet_wrap(~replicate, nrow = 2, ncol = 2)+
  labs(title = NULL,
       x = "Concentration",
       y = "Density")+
  theme_bw()+
  theme(axis.title = element_text(face = 'bold'))

ggplot(dnase.combined, aes(x = conc, y = density, fill = replicate, shape = replicate))+
  geom_point(size = 3, alpha = 0.9)+
  geom_smooth(method = 'loess', aes(color = replicate), se = F, linetype = 'solid')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'

ggplot(DNase, aes(x = conc, y = density, fill = Run))+
  geom_point(size = 1, alpha = 1)+
  geom_smooth(aes(color = Run), method = "loess", se = F, linetype = 'solid')
## `geom_smooth()` using formula = 'y ~ x'
